Like other porcine enteric viruses, SeACoV is transmitted through the fecal-oral route. This has been demonstrated by challenge experiments in pigs using the cell-cultured SeACoV strains (
 Pan et al., 2017; 
 Xu et al., 2019; 
 Zhou et al., 2018b). Diarrhea or vomitus from infected piglets is likely the major transmission route of SeACoV. Other swine CoVs may be able to utilize different routes of infection. For example, PEDV invasion through the nasal cavity (respiratory tract) can also cause intestinal mucosal disease (
 Li et al., 2018b), and PRCV is a pathogenic respiratory mutant of TGEV (
 Wesley and Lager, 2003). Whether aerosolized SeACoV is also infectious should be investigated in the future.
